direct\">biochemical pathway<\/a> in cells for <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Oxidative_phosphorylation\" title=\"Oxidative phosphorylation\">production of energy<\/a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Hans_Adolf_Krebs#cite_note-7\"><span>[<\/span>7<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-8\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Hans_Adolf_Krebs#cite_note-8\"><span>[<\/span>8<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> He is best known for his discoveries of two important chemical reactions in the body, namely the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Urea_cycle\" title=\"Urea cycle\">urea cycle<\/a> and the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Citric_acid_cycle\" title=\"Citric acid cycle\">citric acid cycle<\/a>. The latter, the key sequence of metabolic reactions that produces energy in cells, often eponymously known as the \"Krebs cycle\", earned him a <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize_in_Physiology_or_Medicine\" title=\"Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine\">Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine<\/a> in 1953. With <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Hans_Kornberg\" title=\"Hans Kornberg\">Hans Kornberg<\/a>, he also discovered the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Glyoxylate_cycle\" title=\"Glyoxylate cycle\">glyoxylate cycle<\/a>, which is a slight variation of the citric acid cycle found in plants, bacteria, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Protists\" title=\"Protists\" class=\"mw-redirect\">protists<\/a>, and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Fungi\" title=\"Fungi\" class=\"mw-redirect\">fungi<\/a>.<\/p>","name":"Hans Adolf Krebs","place_of_birth":"Hildesheim ,  Germany","place_of_death":"Oxford ,  England","text":"Hans Adolf Krebs ,  born in Germany , Physiology or Medicine, 1953","year":1953.0}